### Example 2: Diagnostic Context Gathering - AKS Troubleshooting
POST {{AZURE_OPENAI_ENDPOINT}}openai/deployments/{{AZURE_OPENAI_GPT4O_DEPLOYMENT_NAME}}/chat/completions?api-version={{AZURE_OPENAI_GPT4O_API_VERSION}}
Content-Type: application/json
api-key: {{AZURE_OPENAI_API_KEY}}

{
  "messages": [
    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Our Azure Kubernetes Service cluster is experiencing issues."
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I'll help you troubleshoot your AKS cluster issues. To better understand the problem, could you provide:\n1. What symptoms are you observing? (pods not starting, network issues, performance problems, etc.)\n2. What's your cluster size and configuration?\n3. When did the issues start?\n4. Any recent changes or deployments?"
    },
    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Pods are randomly failing with OOMKilled errors. We have a 5-node cluster with Standard_D4s_v3 VMs. This started 2 days ago after we deployed a new version of our main API service."
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "OOMKilled errors indicate your pods are exceeding their memory limits. Since this started after deploying your new API service, it's likely related to that change. Let me help you investigate:\n\n1. First, what are the current resource limits for your API service pods?\n2. How many replicas are you running?\n3. Did the new version introduce any memory-intensive features?\n\nTo gather data, you can run:\n```bash\nkubectl top pods -n <namespace> | grep <api-service-name>\nkubectl describe pod <pod-name> -n <namespace>\n```"
    },
    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "We have 3 replicas with 512Mi memory limit each. The new version added image processing capabilities. The kubectl top shows pods using 480-510Mi before crashing."
    }
  ],
  "max_tokens": 1000,
  "temperature": 0.7
}

